05891nam a22006735i 9781447300021DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20122012xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97814473000217 a10.56687/97814473000212doi  a(DE-B1597)645528  a(OCoLC)794903817  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcGB-BST 7aSOC0040002bisacsh04a364.09222300aCriminalisation and Advanced Marginality :bCritically Exploring the Work of Loïc Wacquant /ced. by Peter Squires, John Lea. 1aBristol : bPolicy Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: reading Loïc Wacquant – opening questions and overview -- tBringing the state back in: understanding neoliberal security -- tThe state, sovereignty and advanced marginality in the city -- tThe third time as farce: whatever happened to the penal state? -- tLoïc Wacquant and Norbert Elias: advanced marginality and the theory of the de-civilising process -- tBeyond the penal state: advanced marginality, social policy and anti-welfarism -- tLoïc Wacquant, gender and cultures of resistance -- tWomen, welfare and the carceral state -- tIllicit economies and the carceral social zone -- tThe universal and the particular in Latin American penal state formation -- tNeoliberal, brutish and short? Cities, inequalities and violences -- tThe wedding of workfare and prisonfare in the 21st century: responses to critics and commentators -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgements -- tNotes on contributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book represents the first full-length critical and interdisciplinary assessment of Loïc Wacquant's work in English. Wacquant's challenging critique of the neo-liberal government of crime and the punitive culture to which this is related has shaken criminology to its foundations. In a bold political analysis he describes how the US-led revolution in law and order has dismantled the welfare state, replacing it with a disciplinary and penal state. Wacquant's analysis also details the spread of neo-liberal crime control measures and the underpinning 'pornographic' discourses of crime across the developed world, although critics have questioned the extent to which this model of criminal justice really is gaining the worldwide dominance alleged. Written by criminologists and policy analysts, Criminalisation and advanced marginality offers a constructive but critical application of Wacquant's ideas. The contributors welcome the opportunity presented by Wacquant's work to re-engage with a radical politics of law and order, criminalisation and marginality, whilst raising issues of gender, resistance, conflict and history which, they argue, help to enrich and further develop Wacquant's analyses. The book concludes with a chapter from Professor Wacquant himself responding to the commentaries upon his work. It fills an important gap in the existing literature and will be exciting reading for academics and students of criminology, social policy and the social sciences more broadly.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCriminology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh1 aHallsworth, Simon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHancock, Lynn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLea, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLea, John, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMartin, Denise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeasor, Lynda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMooney, Gerry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary